{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625816"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17040"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17040"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.13,0.16,0.22,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5284"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAntimalarial medications are crucial for treating infections caused by \u003Cem\u003EPlasmodium\u003C/em\u003E species. These parasites digest haemoglobin in their food vacuoles, producing toxic haem which must be converted to non-toxic haemozoin crystals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of chloroquine against malaria parasites?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits haemozoin formation in the food vacuole","Prevents merozoite formation","Blocks parasite protein synthesis","Disrupts parasite mitochondrial function","Inhibits folate synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChloroquine works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting haemozoin formation in the food vacuole\u003C/strong\u003E of malaria parasites. The drug accumulates in the acidic food vacuole through ion trapping. By preventing the conversion of toxic haem to non-toxic haemozoin, chloroquine causes parasite death through haem-mediated toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents merozoite formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is incorrect as chloroquine specifically targets the food vacuole metabolism rather than merozoite development.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks parasite protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - While protein synthesis disruption may occur as a secondary effect, this is not the primary mechanism through which chloroquine acts.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts parasite mitochondrial function\u003C/strong\u003E - Chloroquine\u0027s main site of action is the food vacuole, not the mitochondria.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits folate synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the mechanism of other antimalarial drugs such as pyrimethamine, but is not how chloroquine works.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloroquine resistance develops through mutations in the parasite\u0027s chloroquine resistance transporter, which reduces drug accumulation in the food vacuole.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chloroquine acts by preventing haemozoin formation in the food vacuole of Plasmodium parasites, leading to toxic haem accumulation.","Chloroquine concentrates in the acidic food vacuole of malaria parasites due to ion trapping.","Resistance to chloroquine occurs through mutations in the Plasmodium falciparum chloroquine resistance transporter."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Gorobets NY, Sedash YV, Singh BK, Poonam, Rathi B. An Overview of Currently Available Antimalarials. Curr Top Med Chem. 2017;17(19):2143-2157. doi:10.2174/1568026617666170130123520"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T16:57:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:58:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9730"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{